<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-06-15T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-06-15T23:00:00-05:00" n="683" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d683">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1111 Bush, Henry J./30:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Swatow</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hinke</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Swatow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-16T12:00:00+08:00">June 16,
                                1935—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received June 16—5:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The following telegram has been received from Drumright<note n="8" xml:id="d683fn8">Everett F. Drumright, Vice Consul at Shanghai,
                                temporarily detailed to Swatow.</note> at Kaying: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“June 16, 10 a.m. Father Bush rescued near Huangpi by military
                                    forces last night and is being escorted to Shihcheng today.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <p>Legation informed.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hinke</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>